.TH "NAVIGATEEVENT.INTERCEPT" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
NavigateEvent.intercept \- NavigateEvent: intercept() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]intercept()\f[B]\f[R] method of the
\f[CR]NavigateEvent\f[R] interface intercepts this navigation, turning
it into a same\-document navigation to the \f[CR]destination\f[R] URL.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
intercept()
intercept(options)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]options\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An options object containing the following properties:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]handler\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A callback function that defines what the navigation handling behavior
should be; it returns a promise.
This function will run after the \f[CR]currentEntry\f[R] property has
been updated.
.TP
\f[B]precommitHandler\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A callback function that defines any behavior that should occur just
before the navigation has committed; it accepts a
\f[CR]NavigationPrecommitController\f[R] object as an argument and
returns a promise.
This function will run before the \f[CR]currentEntry\f[R] property has
been updated.
.TP
\f[B]focusReset\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
Defines the navigation\(cqs focus behavior.
This may take one of the following values:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]after\-transition\f[R]
Once the promise returned by your handler function resolves, the browser
will focus the first element with the \f[CR]autofocus\f[R] attribute, or
the \f[CR]<body>\f[R] element if no element has \f[CR]autofocus\f[R]
set.
This is the default value.
.TP
\f[B]manual\f[R]
Disable the default behavior.
.RE
.TP
\f[B]scroll\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
Defines the navigation\(cqs scrolling behavior.
This may take one of the following values:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]after\-transition\f[R]
Allow the browser to handle scrolling, for example by scrolling to the
relevant fragment identifier if the URL contains a fragment, or
restoring the scroll position to the same place as last time if the page
is reloaded or a page in the history is revisited.
This is the default value.
.TP
\f[B]manual\f[R]
Disable the default behavior.
.RE
.RE
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]InvalidStateError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if the current \f[CR]Document\f[R] is not yet active, or if the
navigation has been cancelled.
.TP
\f[B]SecurityError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
The event was dispatched by a \f[CR]dispatchEvent()\f[R] call, rather
than the user agent.
.IP \(bu 2
The navigation cannot be intercepted
(\f[CR]NavigateEvent.canIntercept\f[R] is \f[CR]false\f[R]).
.IP \(bu 2
A \f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R] callback is provided on a
non\-cancelable event (\f[CR]Event.cancelable\f[R] is \f[CR]false\f[R]).
.RE
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[CR]intercept()\f[R] method is used to implement same\-document
(SPA) navigation behavior when a navigation occurs; for example, when a
link is clicked, a form is submitted, or a programmatic navigation is
initiated (using \f[CR]History.pushState()\f[R],
\f[CR]Window.location\f[R], etc.).
.PP
It does this via a couple of different callbacks, \f[CR]handler()\f[R]
and \f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R].
.SS Handling immediate navigations with \f[CR]handler()\f[R]
The \f[CR]handler()\f[R] callback is run in response to a committed
navigation.
It will run after the \f[CR]currentEntry\f[R] property has been updated,
meaning that a new URL is shown in the browser UI and the history is
updated with a new entry.
.PP
A typical example looks like this, enabling specific content to be
rendered and loaded in response to a certain navigation:
.IP
.EX
navigation.addEventListener(\(dqnavigate\(dq, (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]const\f[R] url = \f[B]new\f[R] URL(event.destination.url);

  \f[B]if\f[R] (url.pathname.startsWith(\(dq/articles/\(dq)) {
    event.intercept({
      \f[B]async\f[R] handler() {
        \f[I]// Fetch the new content and display when ready\f[R]
        \f[B]const\f[R] articleContent = \f[B]await\f[R] getArticleContent(url.pathname);
        renderArticlePage(articleContent);
      },
    });
  }

  \f[I]// Include multiple conditions for different page types here, as needed\f[R]
});
.EE
.PP
\f[CR]handler()\f[R] should be used to implement navigation behavior
where the navigation is committed to: the user should be shown something
new.
.SS Handling precommit actions with \f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R]
However, you might also wish to modify or cancel in\-flight navigation,
or to perform work while the navigation is ongoing and before it is
committed.
This kind of scenario can be dealt with using the
\f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R] callback, which runs before the
\f[CR]currentEntry\f[R] property has been updated and the browser UI
shows the new location.
.PP
For example, if the user navigates to a restricted page and is not
signed in, you may want to redirect the browser to a sign\-in page.
This might be handled like so:
.IP
.EX
navigation.addEventListener(\(dqnavigate\(dq, (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]const\f[R] url = \f[B]new\f[R] URL(event.destination.url);

  \f[B]if\f[R] (url.pathname.startsWith(\(dq/restricted/\(dq) && !userSignedIn) {
    event.intercept({
      \f[B]async\f[R] precommitHandler(controller) {
        controller.redirect(\(dq/signin/\(dq, {
          state: \(dqsignin\-redirect\(dq,
          history: \(dqpush\(dq,
        });
      },
    });
  }
});
.EE
.PP
This pattern is simpler than the alternative of canceling the original
navigation and starting a new one to the redirect location, because it
avoids exposing the intermediate state.
For example, only one \f[CR]navigatesuccess\f[R] or
\f[CR]navigateerror\f[R] event fires, and if the navigation was
triggered by a call to \f[CR]Navigation.navigate()\f[R], the promise
only fulfills once the redirect destination is reached.
.PP
The \f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R] callback takes a
\f[CR]NavigationPrecommitController\f[R] object as an argument, which
contains a \f[CR]redirect()\f[R] method.
The \f[CR]redirect()\f[R] method takes two parameters \(em a string
representing the URL to redirect to, and an optional options object than
can specify state and history behavior.
.PP
\f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R] generally handles any modifications to the
navigation behavior that are required before the destination URL is
actually displayed in the browser, cancelling or redirecting it
somewhere else as required.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Because \f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R] can be used to
cancel navigations, it will only work as expected when the event\(cqs
\f[CR]Event.cancelable\f[R] property is \f[CR]true\f[R].
Calling \f[CR]intercept()\f[R] with a \f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R] on a
non\-cancelable event results in a \f[CR]SecurityError\f[R] being
thrown.
.RE
.SS Responding to navigation success or failure
When the promises returned by the \f[CR]intercept()\f[R] handler
functions fulfill, the \f[CR]Navigation\f[R] object\(cqs
\f[CR]navigatesuccess\f[R] event fires, allowing you to run cleanup code
after a successful navigation has completed.
If those promises reject, meaning the navigation has failed,
\f[CR]navigateerror\f[R] fires instead, allowing you to gracefully
handle the failure case.
.PP
There is also a \f[CR]finished\f[R] property on the return value of
navigation methods (such as \f[CR]Navigation.navigate()\f[R]), which
fulfills or rejects at the same time as the aforementioned events are
fired, providing another path for handling the success and failure
cases.
.SS Interaction between \f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R] and \f[CR]handler()\f[R]
Both \f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R] and \f[CR]handler()\f[R] callbacks
can be included inside the same \f[CR]intercept()\f[R] call.
In such cases, the order of operations is as follows:
.IP "1." 3
First, the \f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R] handler runs.
.RS 4
.IP \(bu 2
When the \f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R] promise fulfills, the navigation
commits.
.IP \(bu 2
If the \f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R] rejects, the
\f[CR]navigateerror\f[R] event fires, the \f[CR]committed\f[R] and
\f[CR]finished\f[R] promises reject, and the navigation is cancelled.
.RE
.IP "2." 3
When the navigation commits, a new \f[CR]NavigationHistoryEntry\f[R] is
created for the navigation, and its \f[CR]committed\f[R] promise
fulfills.
.IP "3." 3
Next, the \f[CR]handler()\f[R] promise runs.
.RS 4
.IP \(bu 2
When the \f[CR]handler()\f[R] promise fulfills and the
\f[CR]navigatesuccess\f[R] event fires, the navigation
\f[CR]finished\f[R] promise fulfills as well, to indicate the navigation
is finished.
.IP \(bu 2
If \f[CR]handler()\f[R] rejects, the \f[CR]navigateerror\f[R] event
fires, the \f[CR]finished\f[R] promise rejects, and the navigation is
canceled.
.RE
.PP
Note that the above process is upheld even across multiple
\f[CR]intercept()\f[R] calls on the same \f[CR]NavigateEvent\f[R].
All \f[CR]precommitHandler()\f[R] callbacks are called first, and when
all of them resolve, the navigation commits, and all the
\f[CR]handler()\f[R] callbacks are called.
.SS Controlling focus behavior
By default, after a navigation handled using \f[CR]intercept()\f[R] has
occurred, the document focus will reset to the first element in the DOM
with an \f[CR]autofocus\f[R] attribute set, or otherwise to the
\f[CR]<body>\f[R] element, if no \f[CR]autofocus\f[R] attribute is set.
If you want to override this behavior, to manually implement a more
accessible focus position on navigation (for example, the new top\-level
heading), you can do so by setting the \f[CR]focusReset\f[R] option to
\f[CR]manual\f[R].
.IP
.EX
navigation.addEventListener(\(dqnavigate\(dq, (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]const\f[R] url = \f[B]new\f[R] URL(event.destination.url);

  \f[B]if\f[R] (url.pathname.startsWith(\(dq/articles/\(dq)) {
    event.intercept({
      focusReset: manual,
      \f[B]async\f[R] handler() {
        \f[I]// Fetch the new content and display when ready\f[R]
        \f[B]const\f[R] articleContent = \f[B]await\f[R] getArticleContent(url.pathname);
        renderArticlePage(articleContent);
        \f[I]// Handle page focus with a custom function\f[R]
        setPageFocus();
      },
    });
  }
});
.EE
.SS Controlling scroll behavior
After an \f[CR]intercept()\f[R] navigation has completed, the following
scrolling behavior occurs:
.IP \(bu 2
For \f[CR]push\f[R] and \f[CR]replace\f[R] navigations (see
\f[CR]Navigation.navigate()\f[R]), the browser will attempt to scroll to
the fragment given by \f[CR]event.destination.url\f[R].
If there is no fragment available, it will reset the scroll position to
the top of the page.
.IP \(bu 2
For \f[CR]traverse\f[R] and \f[CR]reload\f[R] navigations, the behavior
is similar to \f[CR]push\f[R] and \f[CR]replace\f[R] navigations, but
the browser delays its scroll restoration logic until the
\f[CR]intercept()\f[R] promise fulfills.
It will perform no scroll restoration if the promise rejects.
If the user has scrolled during the transition then no scroll
restoration will be performed.
.PP
If you want to turn this behavior off, you can do so by setting the
\f[CR]scroll\f[R] option to \f[CR]manual\f[R].
.IP
.EX
navigation.addEventListener(\(dqnavigate\(dq, (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]const\f[R] url = \f[B]new\f[R] URL(event.destination.url);

  \f[B]if\f[R] (url.pathname.startsWith(\(dq/articles/\(dq)) {
    event.intercept({
      scroll: manual,
      \f[B]async\f[R] handler() {
        \f[I]// Fetch the new content and display when ready\f[R]
        \f[B]const\f[R] articleContent = \f[B]await\f[R] getArticleContent(url.pathname);
        renderArticlePage(articleContent);
        \f[I]// Handle scroll behavior with a custom function\f[R]
        setScroll();
      },
    });
  }
});
.EE
.PP
If you want to manually trigger the default scrolling behavior described
earlier (maybe you want to reset the scroll position to the top of the
page early, before the full navigation has finished), you can do so by
calling \f[CR]NavigateEvent.scroll()\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Handling a navigation using \f[CR]intercept()\f[R]
.IP
.EX
navigation.addEventListener(\(dqnavigate\(dq, (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[I]// Exit early if this navigation shouldn\(aqt be intercepted,\f[R]
  \f[I]// e.g. if the navigation is cross\-origin, or a download request\f[R]
  \f[B]if\f[R] (shouldNotIntercept(event)) \f[B]return\f[R];

  \f[B]const\f[R] url = \f[B]new\f[R] URL(event.destination.url);

  \f[B]if\f[R] (url.pathname.startsWith(\(dq/articles/\(dq)) {
    event.intercept({
      \f[B]async\f[R] handler() {
        \f[I]// The URL has already changed, so show a placeholder while\f[R]
        \f[I]// fetching the new content, such as a spinner or loading page\f[R]
        renderArticlePagePlaceholder();

        \f[I]// Fetch the new content and display when ready\f[R]
        \f[B]const\f[R] articleContent = \f[B]await\f[R] getArticleContent(url.pathname);
        renderArticlePage(articleContent);
      },
    });
  }
});
.EE
.SS Using \f[CR]focusReset\f[R] and \f[CR]scroll\f[R]
Form submission can be detected by querying for the
\f[CR]NavigateEvent.formData\f[R] property.
The following example turns any form submission into one which stays on
the current page.
In this case, you don\(cqt update the DOM, so you can cancel any default
reset and scroll behavior using \f[CR]focusReset\f[R] and
\f[CR]scroll\f[R].
.IP
.EX
navigation.addEventListener(\(dqnavigate\(dq, (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]if\f[R] (event.formData && event.canIntercept) {
    \f[I]// User submitted a POST form to a same\-domain URL\f[R]
    \f[I]// (If canIntercept is false, the event is just informative:\f[R]
    \f[I]// you can\(aqt intercept this request, although you could\f[R]
    \f[I]// likely still call .preventDefault() to stop it completely).\f[R]

    event.intercept({
      \f[I]// Since we don\(aqt update the DOM in this navigation,\f[R]
      \f[I]// don\(aqt allow focus or scrolling to reset:\f[R]
      focusReset: \(dqmanual\(dq,
      scroll: \(dqmanual\(dq,
      \f[B]async\f[R] handler() {
        \f[B]await\f[R] fetch(event.destination.url, {
          method: \(dqPOST\(dq,
          body: event.formData,
        });
        \f[I]// You could navigate again with {history: \(aqreplace\(aq} to\f[R]
        \f[I]// change the URL here, which might indicate \(dqdone\(dq\f[R]
      },
    });
  }
});
.EE
